descript.abstract: This data set represents terrestrial vegetation along the portion the Salinas River in Monterey County and several of its tributaries. The Nature Conservancy (TNC), California defined "Gallery" vegetation classes as mature riparian forests dominated by native species with a tree density greater than forty percent. The data set was developed by Aerial Information Systems in May 2008. Refer to mnt_SalinasR_Veg_Report.doc for more info
descript.purpose: The data set will be used by TNC CA, Science to map and determine the extent of native riparian vegetation along the Salinas River and its major tributaries, to identify significant areas of invasive species such as Giant Cane, and to inform an assessment of potential wildlife corridors along the riparian corridor to the adjacent upland habitats in the coastal ranges.
descript.supplinf: A complete report is available at: http://www.nrm.dfg.ca.gov/FileHandler.ashx?DocumentID=17941

0=no field check;1=AIS photointerpreters had questions; 2=questions answered
name of mapping unit which is sometimes at the alliance level
attr.attrdefs: based on vegetation alliances in the Manual of California Vegetation 1995

attr.attrdef: The name of the community or hierarchical level within NVCS; for mapunits that are not natural vegetation, the Wildlife Habitat Relationships classification is used
the NVCS level the Salinas River mapping unit corresponds to
macrogroup level of the National Vegetation Classification System
Crosswalk to wildlife habitat relationship classification

The global rarity rank of the plant community mapped (only for alliances and associations). G1 and S1: Fewer than 6 viable occurrences worldwide and/or 2000 acres; G2 and S2: 6-20 viable occurrences worldwide and/or 2000-10,000 acres; G3 and S3: 21-100 viable occurrences worldwide and/or 10,000-50,000 acres; G4 and S4: Greater than 100 viable occurrences worldwide and/or greater than 50,000 acres; G5 and S5: Community demonstrably secure due to secure worldwide and statewide abundance

overview.eadetcit: Note: certain fields have been added by the Department of Fish and Game's Vegetation Classification and Mapping Program. These include crosswalks to the Wildlife Habitat Relationships and CalVeg classification systems and the fields relating the mapping units to the National Vegetation Classification System as it is described for California in the 2nd edition of the Manual of California Vegetation
